      <div class="section">
        <h2>Why Most Tracking Apps Fail Men Over 40</h2>
        <p>The tracking apps that dominate the market — MyFitnessPal, Cronometer, Lose It — are genuinely impressive pieces of software. They can track thousands of nutrients, sync with wearables, generate weekly reports, and log every gram of food you've ever eaten.</p>
        <p>They're also why most men over 40 give up on tracking within two weeks. The problem isn't discipline. It's friction. Every extra field, every calorie goal you don't care about, every pop-up upsell — each one is a small tax on your attention. And attention is exactly what you're trying to conserve when you're building a new habit.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <h3>The abandonment problem nobody talks about</h3>
          <p>Most nutrition tracking apps have extremely high dropout rates — often <strong>over 80% within the first month</strong>. The most cited reason isn't lack of motivation — it's that the apps feel like a part-time job. For men over 40 who already have full lives, that friction is a dealbreaker.</p>
        </div>

