      <div class="section">
        <h2>The 80/20 Truth About Your Diet After 40</h2>
        <p>Here's something that rarely gets said out loud: most men over 40 eat the same 8–12 foods on rotation every week. Eggs in the morning. Chicken or a burger at lunch. Maybe Greek yogurt. A protein shake somewhere. Steak on weekends.</p>
        <p>You don't need a database of 8 million foods. You need <em>your</em> 10 foods — with their protein numbers already in front of you. That's the entire premise behind keeping protein tracking simple. You don't need to discover new foods to hit your protein goal. You need to see <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/" style="font-weight:600;">what 120g actually looks like</a> in the foods you already eat — and then make sure you're hitting that number consistently.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <h3>The real problem isn't knowledge</h3>
          <p>Most men over 40 know they should eat more protein. The problem is they can't see their number. By dinner time, they genuinely don't know if they've hit 60g or 110g. That gap — between intention and visibility — is where muscle is quietly lost.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="section">
        <h2>What "Easy" Actually Looks Like — The 5-Step System</h2>
        <p>Easy doesn't mean skipping tracking altogether. Skipping it means going back to guessing — and guessing is how most men end up eating 70g on a day they thought was "pretty good." Easy means building a system with almost no friction between you and your number.</p>

        <div class="steps">
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">1</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <h4>Set one number</h4>
              <p>Your daily protein target in grams. Multiply your bodyweight in pounds by 0.64, or use the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-calculator-men-over-40/" style="font-weight:600;">protein calculator</a> to get your exact number. That's the only goal you're tracking. Most men aim for roughly <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/30-gram-protein-rule/" style="font-weight:600;">30g per meal</a> — here's why that works.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">2</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <h4>Pre-load your common foods</h4>
              <p>You eat the same 8–12 foods 80% of the time. Chicken breast, Greek yogurt, eggs, protein shake, cottage cheese. Set those up as one-tap shortcuts. You should never be searching a database for something you eat every week.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">3</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <h4>Log at the meal, not end of day</h4>
              <p>End-of-day logging is a memory exercise, not a tracking exercise. Log right after you eat — 15 seconds and it's accurate. End-of-day reconstruction takes 5 minutes and is usually 20–30g off.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">4</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <h4>Watch one visual indicator</h4>
              <p>A progress ring, a bar, a number climbing toward a target. One visual. Not a dashboard of six metrics. Your brain responds to clear, singular progress signals — it's how habits form.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="step">
            <div class="step-num">5</div>
            <div class="step-body">
              <h4>Stop when you hit your goal</h4>
              <p>No calorie ceiling to stay under, no fat macro to hit. You reached your protein target — you're done. That moment of completion is what makes people come back tomorrow.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="related-link">
